        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1987-01-28T15:58:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1987-01-28T15:58:00-05:00" n="348"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                <head>348. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Tunisia<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d348fn1">Source: Department of State, Executive
                        Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SS_1">S/S</gloss> Records, 1987 Nodis
                        Telegrams: Lot 95D26, Tunis Nodis 1987. Secret; Immediate; Nodis. Drafted by
                        O’Neill; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_GDD_1">Gregg</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_PWR_1">Pearson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_QK_1"
                            >Quinn</persName>, and Laurie Tracy (<gloss target="#t_SSO_1"
                            >S/S–O</gloss>); approved by <persName corresp="#p_UM_1"
                            >Ussery</persName>. Sent for information to Algiers, Rabat, Ndjamena,
                        Cairo, Paris, and Brussels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">23812.</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1987-01-28T20:58:00+00:00">January 28, 1987, 2058Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Tunisian Ambassador’s Call on Vice President <persName corresp="#p_BGHW_1"
                            >Bush</persName>.</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Secret—Entire text.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Introduction and Summary: On January 23, Vice President <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGHW_1">Bush</persName> met with Tunisian Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> to accept on behalf of
                        President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> a personal message
                        from President <persName corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>.<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d348fn2">Bourguiba’s message was not found.</note> In relaying
                        message, <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> assured Vice
                        President concerning Tunisian contacts with Libya and expressed <gloss
                            target="#t_GOT_1">GOT</gloss> satisfaction about U.S.-Tunisian military
                        contingency planning.<note n="3" xml:id="d348fn3">See <ref target="#d345"
                                >Document 345</ref>.</note> Discussion also focussed on Chad,
                        Libya’s relations with Morocco and Algeria, <persName corresp="#p_BH_4"
                            >Bourguiba</persName>’s health, Tunisia’s economy and U.S.
                        assistance.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Libya. <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> opened
                        conversation by referring to <persName corresp="#p_QM_1"
                        >Qadhafi</persName>’s isolation in North Africa. Rapprochement with Algeria
                        had not gone well, and Libya had suffered serious defeats in Chad. <persName
                            corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> said he had been instructed by
                            <persName corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName> to advise President
                            <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> that <gloss
                            target="#t_GOT_1">GOT</gloss> is not about to “save” <persName
                            corresp="#p_QM_1">Qadhafi</persName> from his isolation by normalizing
                        ties with Libya. There will be no normalization without Libyan compensation
                        for expelled Tunisian workers and for $200 million in seized assets.
                            <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> expressed <gloss
                            target="#t_GOT_1">GOT</gloss>’s conviction that <persName
                            corresp="#p_QM_1">Qadhafi</persName> will be unable to meet Tunisian
                        demands.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>To Vice President’s query about Morocco’s relations with Libya, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> responded that Hassan had told
                            <gloss target="#t_GOT_1">GOT</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_FONMIN_1">FonMin</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MH_1">Mabrouk</persName> that <gloss target="#t_GOM_1"
                            >GOM</gloss>’s break with Libya was final. Meetings between Algeria and
                        Libya had been a signal to Morocco. <persName corresp="#p_QM_1"
                            >Qadhafi</persName>’s flirtation with Morocco is over. With regard to
                        Algerian-Libyan ties, <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName>
                        noted that while <gloss target="#t_GOA_1">GOA</gloss> recognizes that Libyan
                        situation is a “mess,” <persName corresp="#p_BC_1">Bendjedid</persName> is
                        reluctant to condemn <persName corresp="#p_QM_1">Qadhafi</persName> in part
                        because of situation in Western Sahara. Libya and <gloss target="#t_GOA_1"
                            >GOA</gloss> share positions in OPEC; that is their only common
                        interest.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Chad. <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> expressed <gloss
                            target="#t_GOT_1">GOT</gloss> satisfaction at losses <persName
                            corresp="#p_QM_1">Qadhafi</persName> has suffered in Chad and for U.S.
                        and French support for Chad. He said <persName corresp="#p_BH_4"
                            >Bourguiba</persName> had discussed Chadian situation with <persName
                            corresp="#p_MF_1">Mitterrand</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CJ_1"
                            >Chirac</persName> during his recent visit to Paris. Tunisians are
                        gratified to see change in <persName corresp="#p_MF_1"
                        >Mitterrand</persName>’s attitude toward Chad. With French logistical <pb
                            facs="0763" n="724" xml:id="pg_724"/> support, Habre dealt a severe blow
                        to <persName corresp="#p_QM_1">Qadhafi</persName>. <gloss target="#t_GOT_1"
                            >GOT</gloss> is concerned as to how <persName corresp="#p_QM_1"
                            >Qadhafi</persName> might respond to this defeat. At present, only
                        pressure being placed on him is from Chad.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Contingency Planning. <persName corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>
                        also instructed <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> to relay
                        to President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> his
                        gratification over good work accomplished by <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                            >US</gloss> and Tunisian military on joint contingency planning. Meeting
                        at Stuttgart in November resulted in a new phase in USG-GOT cooperation that
                        will assure Tunisia’s security in event of Libyan aggression. He expressed
                        hope that next meeting in March in Tunis will be equally successful.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>Vice President expressed appreciation on behalf of President <persName
                            corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> for messages on Libya and USG-GOT
                        military cooperation and inquired about President <persName
                            corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>’s health. Speaking to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName>’s continuing attention to detail
                        in governing Tunisia, <persName corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName>
                        referred to President’s vision in initiating structural adjustment program
                        to turn around Tunisia’s economic crisis. He said that with <gloss
                            target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> help 1987 will be a better year than 1986
                        for Tunisia.</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>U.S. Assistance. Referring to the U.S. budget squeeze, Vice President said
                        that Secretaries <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_WCWC_1">Weinberger</persName> had complained
                        bitterly about cuts which their departments had to absorb. Despite foreign
                        aid reductions, <gloss target="#t_USG_1">USG</gloss> remains determined to
                        try to assist Tunisia. Noting that U.S.-Tunisian relations are built on
                        mutual respect for shared values, Vice President asked <persName
                            corresp="#p_BYH_1">Ben Yahia</persName> to convey to President <persName
                            corresp="#p_BH_4">Bourguiba</persName> President <persName
                            corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName>’s assurance of a U.S. commitment to
                        Tunisia’s prosperity.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Shultz</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
